__Sentiment Analysis: Luke's Lobster at Back Bay__

In order to understand customer reviews, below codes will help identify tones of customer reviews to predict their rating for Luke's Lobster at Back Bay.

See reference here at [https://www.yelp.com/biz/lukes-lobster-back-bay-boston?osq=luke%27s]

Create a new list to store collected reviews¶

This list will store data that is scraped from the website. For each review, its scraping date, URL, review text, and rating/stars would be stored as a dictionary in the list.

In [ ]:
reviews_one_store = []
condition = True

#collect all reviews
while (condition):
    reviews           = driver.find_elements_by_xpath("//div[@class='lemon--div__373c0__1mboc review__373c0__13kpL border-color--default__373c0__3-ifU']")
    r                 = 0
    for r in range(len(reviews)):
        one_review                   = {}
        one_review['scrapping_date'] = datetime.datetime.now()
        one_review['url']     = driver.current_url
        soup                         = BeautifulSoup(reviews[r].get_attribute('innerHTML')) 
        try:
            one_review_raw = reviews[r].get_attribute('innerHTML')
        except:
            one_review_raw = ""
        one_review['review_raw'] = one_review_raw
        
        try:
            one_review_text = soup.find('span', attrs={'class':'lemon--span__373c0__3997G raw__373c0__3rcx7'}).text
        except:
            one_review_text = ""
        one_review['one_review_text'] = one_review_text
        
        try:
            one_review_stars = re.findall('[0-9] [Ss]tar',reviews[r].get_attribute('innerHTML'))[0]
        except:
            one_review_stars = ""
        one_review['one_review_stars'] = one_review_stars
        reviews_one_store.append(one_review)
    try:
        driver.find_element_by_xpath("//span[@class='icon--24-chevron-right-v2 navigation-button-icon__373c0__2Fl7a css-12anxc3']").click()
        time.sleep(random.randint(1,3))
    except:
        break

len(reviews_one_store)

Data Cleaning¶

Scraped data may not be as decent as we want. To make it readable and understandable, some cleaning process is necessary.

In [ ]:
# Transform data to a dataframe
a = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(reviews_one_store)
#back up orignial scraped data
b = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(reviews_one_store)
#check details of a review
BeautifulSoup(a.review_raw.iloc[0]).text
b['review_raw'].map(lambda a: BeautifulSoup(a).text)[0]

#extract details and create new columns
# state
a['State'] =  a['review_raw'].map(lambda a: BeautifulSoup(a).text).str.extract('([A-Z][A-Z])[0-9]')[[0]] 
# city name
a['City'] =  a['review_raw'].map(lambda a: BeautifulSoup(a).text).str.extract('([A-Z][.])(Elite .2020)?([A-Z]\w+.? ?\w+? ?\w+? ?\w+? ?\w+?)(,)')[[2]] 
# customer full name
a['Customer Name'] = a['review_raw'].map(lambda a: BeautifulSoup(a).text).str.extract('(\w+ [A-Z].)') 
#review date
a['Review Date'] = a['review_raw'].map(lambda a: BeautifulSoup(a).text).str.extract('([0-1]?[0-9]/[0-9]?[0-9]/[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9])') 
#no.of contacts and reviews on yelp.com
a['No. of Contribution'] = a['review_raw'].map(lambda a: BeautifulSoup(a).text).str.extract('([0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?[0-9]?)([0-9][\/][1-9][0-9][\/])')[[0]]
# rating of Luke's Lobster
a['Rating'] = a['one_review_stars'].map(lambda a: BeautifulSoup(a).text).str.extract('([0-5]) ([Ss].)')[[0]]

#reorder and rearrange columns
a = a[['scrapping_date','url','Customer Name','State','City','Rating','Review Date','No. of Contribution','one_review_text']]

#export to excel
a.to_csv('Lukes Lobster.csv', index = True)

#close driver
driver.close()

Predict with KNN¶

Define functions¶

To get the best prediction accuracy and authenticity, a good parameter k is needed. To find out this best k, functions are established to help.

Function parameterdf(max_k) is defined to predict rating based on the sentiment analysis result from validating data with k = 1 to max_k.

In [31]:
def parameterdf(max_k):
    k            = 1;
    results_list = [];
    max_k_nn     = max_k +1
    for k in range(1,max_k_nn):
        clf      = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k).fit(X_train, Y_train)
        results_list.append(
                np.concatenate(
                        [#use only validating data to check for best parameter
                                clf.predict(X_valid),
                        ])
        )
    review_results_knn              = pd.DataFrame(results_list).transpose()
    return review_results_knn

Function conf_matrix(Y_valid, k) is defined to construct a confusion matrix to show the predicted values and true values from validating data with a inputted k value. Different k(s) can be used to construct the matrix and compare the results.

In [32]:
def conf_matrix(Y_valid, k):
    Y_valid = Y_valid
    n = k-1
    matrix_knn = confusion_matrix(Y_valid, review_results_knn[n], labels = [1,2,3,4,5]) 
    return matrix_knn

Function accuracy_valid(matrix) is defined to calculate the accuracy rate based on a confusion matrix. The result from conf_matrix(Y_valid,k) can be used here. Function maxaccuracy(max_k) is defined to find out the hihest accuracy rate with parameter k from 1 to maximum k, with the validating data. After this, the best k, which produces the highest accuracy rate will be found.

Note: conf_matrix(Y_valid,k) must be defined before maxaccuracy(max_k).

In [34]:
def accuracy_valid(matrix):
    for i in range(5):
        if i == 0 :
            correct_rate_knn = matrix[i,i]
        else:
            correct_rate_knn = matrix[i,i] + matrix[i-1,i] + matrix[i,i-1]
    accuracy = correct_rate_knn / len(Y_valid)
    return accuracy  
def maxaccuracy(max_k):
    accuracy = {}
    for k in range(1,max_k+1):
       acc = accuracy_valid(conf_matrix(Y_valid,k)) 
       accuracy.update({k:acc})
    most_acc = max(accuracy.values())
    for key,value in accuracy.items():
        if(value == most_acc):
            k = key
    return print('The best parameter k is',k,'with an accuracy of',round(most_acc,2))

Test prediction on testing data¶

Before starting, function accuracy_test(matrix) is defined to calculate accuracy rate of a confusion matrix with testing data.

In [47]:
def accuracy_test(matrix):
    for i in range(5):
        if i == 0 :
            correct_rate_knn = matrix[i,i]
        else:
            correct_rate_knn = matrix[i,i] + matrix[i-1,i] + matrix[i,i-1]
    accuracy = round(correct_rate_knn / len(Y_test),4)
    return accuracy

More Applications¶

This model is able to use sentiment analysis to predict a Yelp rating based on customer reviews, with an accuracy rate around 70%. The model thus can be implemented to reviews with no rating or any writing comment content.

That is to be said, this model can also analysis and predict a rating for reviews/comments on Luke's Lobster's other platform, such as Instagram and Facebook, to understand customers' attitude and real thoughts (in the sense of the rating) of the restaurant.

In addition, simply by changing the data, this model can be applied to a variety of content, such as social platform comments and written complaints on surveys, to help the business understand their "rating" in the market.
